"Everything has a price" has numerous ethical implications. When things have a monetary value, it might encourage people and organizations to put money above ethics or morality. Corruption, exploitation, and market manipulation may harm society. This approach may also commodify previously unvalued items and services. This may erode moral ideals and beliefs that are not market-driven. For instance, selling human organs might exploit vulnerable people and create a divide between those who can afford them and those who cannot. When everything has a price, it may also foster consumerism, when people buy things regardless of their morality or ethics. This neglects social and environmental problems and harms people and society. Since everything has a price, morality and profit might conflict. Individuals and organizations must weigh the ethical consequences of their activities and balance financial gain with morality and ethics. 